{"id": "2026-07-18-news-us-mounts-seventh-straight-night-of-strikes-on-i", "date": "2026-07-18", "stream": "news", "headline": "US mounts seventh straight night of strikes on Iran, broadening targets as Gulf states drawn in", "summary": "The US carried out a seventh consecutive night of strikes on Iran hitting bridges, power and water infrastructure and declared the wave over, while Iran keeps firing on Gulf states hosting US forces.", "url": "https://www.srf.ch/news/international/nahost/krieg-im-nahen-osten-usa-erklaeren-siebte-angriffswelle-im-iran-fuer-beendet", "source_domain": "srf.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["ongoing since 2026-06-20"], "topics": ["geopolitics"], "importance": 3, "display_body": "The US mounted a seventh consecutive night of airstrikes on Iran overnight into Saturday 18 July, and by mid-morning declared the wave concluded — while visibly widening its target set beyond military installations. Al Jazeera reported the latest strikes hit bridges and energy infrastructure and cut off water to villages in southern Iran, which its correspondent framed as a broadening of the campaign from narrowly military objectives toward civilian infrastructure. Swiss broadcaster SRF reported that Washington had formally called the seventh strike wave over, even as Iran continues to fire on the Gulf states hosting US forces. The exchange extends an escalation that has drawn US bases across the Gulf into direct fire since the Strait of Hormuz standoff sharpened in June, with both sides publicly rejecting the negotiated pause each accuses the other of refusing.", "why": "A bombing campaign now in its seventh straight night, reaching bridges, power and water supplies and pulling Gulf states into direct exchanges, raises the risk of a wider regional war and keeps Hormuz shipping and energy markets on edge.", "thread_id": "2026-06-20-cyber-papers-iran-closes-strait-of-hormuz-again-over-israeli", "first_seen_date": "2026-06-20", "event_date": "2026-07-18", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-18-news-zelensky-sacks-defence-minister-fedorov-triggeri", "date": "2026-07-18", "stream": "news", "headline": "Zelensky sacks defence minister Fedorov, triggering renewed protests in Kyiv", "summary": "President Zelensky dismissed 35-year-old defence minister Mykhailo Fedorov on 15 July, sparking mass protests in Kyiv that continued Saturday amid a doctrine clash over military modernisation.", "url": "https://www.letemps.ch/monde/volodymyr-zelensky-fragilise-l-ukraine-en-ecartant-le-jeune-architecte-de-l-armee-de-drones-au-profit-de-la-vieille-garde", "source_domain": "letemps.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["geopolitics", "politics"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Thousands rallied again in Kyiv on Saturday 18 July against President Volodymyr Zelensky's dismissal of defence minister Mykhailo Fedorov, deepening a political crisis that opened when Zelensky sacked him on Wednesday 15 July. Fedorov, 35 — the youngest defence minister in Ukraine's history and the figure most identified with its drone-warfare programme — was removed in a government reshuffle that Le Temps reads as a clash of doctrine between a younger, technology-driven generation and older commanders still shaped by Soviet-era methods. The upheaval lands despite a run of better news for Kyiv: a 90 billion euro EU loan, reinforced backing from the coalition of the willing, and Ukrainian strikes on military and energy sites deep inside Russia.", "why": "Sidelining the minister most associated with Ukraine's drone edge — while Moscow shows no interest in negotiating — risks fracturing national unity at a moment Kyiv can least afford it.", "thread_id": "2026-07-18-news-zelensky-sacks-defence-minister-fedorov-triggeri", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-18", "event_date": "2026-07-15", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-18-news-trump-administration-weakens-endangered-species", "date": "2026-07-18", "stream": "news", "headline": "Trump administration weakens Endangered Species Act protections", "summary": "The US administration finalised two rules on 17 July narrowing the Endangered Species Act, ending automatic protection for threatened species and letting economic and security factors weigh in critical-habitat decisions.", "url": "https://www.letemps.ch/articles/l-administration-trump-affaiblit-la-protection-du-grizzly-de-l-alaska-et-du-pygargue-a-tete-blanche", "source_domain": "letemps.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["single-source"], "topics": ["politics", "world"], "importance": 1, "display_body": "The Trump administration finalised two rollbacks to the Endangered Species Act (ESA — the 1973 US law protecting at-risk wildlife) on Friday 17 July, citing economic and national-security priorities. One change repeals the rule that automatically extended the Act's full protections to species merely listed as threatened; the other lets the government weigh economic and national-security considerations when deciding whether an area qualifies as critical habitat for a protected species. Emblematic animals such as the Alaskan grizzly and the bald eagle — the US national bird — are among those covered by the weakened framework.", "why": "It marks a further narrowing of America's flagship conservation law, shifting its default posture from protection toward development.", "thread_id": "2026-07-18-news-trump-administration-weakens-endangered-species", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-18", "event_date": "2026-07-17", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-18-news-cadmium-contamination-draws-scrutiny-in-swiss-fo", "date": "2026-07-18", "stream": "news", "headline": "Cadmium contamination draws scrutiny in Swiss food", "summary": "Toxic heavy metal cadmium is drawing scrutiny in Swiss diets; exposure appears lower than in France, where the National Assembly passed a June 2026 bill to cut it in farm soils, but Swiss data remain sparse.", "url": "https://www.letemps.ch/articles/metal-lourd-toxique-le-cadmium-s-invite-aussi-dans-les-assiettes-helvetiques", "source_domain": "letemps.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["health", "switzerland"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Cadmium — a toxic heavy metal that accumulates in the body over time — is drawing fresh scrutiny in Switzerland's food supply, Le Temps reported on Saturday 18 July, though Swiss exposure appears lower than in neighbouring France. In France, roughly one resident in two exceeds the at-risk concentration threshold, prompting the National Assembly to pass a bill in June 2026 aimed at curbing cadmium in agricultural soils, the main route by which it enters the food chain. Swiss contamination looks milder, but the underlying data are patchy and specialists urge caution rather than reassurance.", "why": "It adds another contaminant — after mercury, pesticides and microplastics — to the list of everyday dietary exposures, and highlights how thin Switzerland's own monitoring data still are.", "thread_id": "2026-07-18-news-cadmium-contamination-draws-scrutiny-in-swiss-fo", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-18", "event_date": "2026-07-18", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-18-news-heatwave-grips-switzerland-fire-bans-gotthard-ta", "date": "2026-07-18", "stream": "news", "headline": "Heatwave grips Switzerland: fire bans, Gotthard tailbacks, comparisons to 1540", "summary": "A summer heatwave has brought fire bans, dying fish and a 20km Gotthard tailback on 18 July, with climate historian Christian Pfister likening 2026 to the extreme summer of 1540.", "url": "https://www.srf.ch/news/international/wetterextreme-nehmen-zu-befuerchte-dass-wir-2026-einen-analogen-fall-zu-1540-haben", "source_domain": "srf.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["ongoing since 2026-07-13"], "topics": ["switzerland"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "A summer heatwave tightened its grip on Switzerland this week, with fire bans now in force, a 20-kilometre tailback of up to three hours at the Gotthard's north portal on Saturday 18 July, and fish dying in overheated eastern-Swiss waters. Climate historian Christian Pfister told SRF he fears 2026 could become a modern analogue of 1540 — the year of a legendary Europe-wide megadrought — as heat, drought and wildfire risk compound. The developments follow SRF Meteo's warning a week earlier that 2026 could surpass the record century summer of 2003 if August stays hot.", "why": "Beyond the immediate disruption — grilling bans, Alpine traffic, stressed rivers — a sustained heatwave strains water, agriculture and infrastructure, and the 1540 comparison underscores how far outside the historical envelope recent Swiss summers are running.", "thread_id": "2026-07-13-news-switzerland-braces-for-new-heatwave-as-2026-near", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-13", "event_date": "2026-07-18", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
{"id": "2026-07-18-news-switzerland-steps-up-its-arctic-engagement", "date": "2026-07-18", "stream": "news", "headline": "Switzerland steps up its Arctic engagement", "summary": "Bern is deepening its Arctic role with a new parliamentary group and a science-and-dialogue strategy, defending its Arctic Council observer status held since 2017.", "url": "https://www.letemps.ch/monde/la-suisse-et-l-arctique-berne-privilegie-une-approche-fondee-sur-la-science-et-le-dialogue", "source_domain": "letemps.ch", "tier": "T2", "tags": [], "topics": ["switzerland", "politics"], "importance": 1, "display_body": "Switzerland is quietly stepping up its Arctic engagement, Le Temps reported on Friday 17 July, with a newly formed parliamentary group and a science-and-dialogue strategy to justify a role in a region where it has no coastline and no vote. Bern, an observer on the Arctic Council since 2017, argues that the Alps and the Arctic share many of the same challenges and points to Switzerland's more-than-150-year tradition of cryosphere (snow-and-ice) research. Former EPFL president Patrick Aebischer is championing a lighter, more community-focused model of polar science aboard the laboratory sailboat Forel, framed explicitly as scientific diplomacy.", "why": "It is a small but telling example of how a landlocked state seeks influence in climate-critical regions through research rather than territory.", "thread_id": "2026-07-18-news-switzerland-steps-up-its-arctic-engagement", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-18", "event_date": "2026-07-17", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": ""}
